{
  "local_port": 58952,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some yummy vegetarian recipes?",
  "response": "Here are some delicious vegetarian recipes you might enjoy:\n\n1. **Vegetarian Chili**\nIngredients:\n- 2 tablespoons olive oil\n- 1 large onion, chopped\n- 3 cloves garlic, minced\n- 1 bell pepper, chopped\n- 2 carrots, chopped\n- 2 celery stalks, chopped\n- 1 can black beans, drained and rinsed\n- 1 can kidney beans, drained and rinsed\n- 1 can corn kernels, drained\n- 1 can diced tomatoes\n- 1 cup vegetable broth\n- 2 tablespoons chili powder\n- 1 teaspoon cumin\n- Salt and pepper to taste\n- Optional toppings: shredded cheese, sour cream, avocado, cilantro\n\nDirections:\n1. Heat olive oil in a large pot over medium heat. Add onions and garlic; saut\u00e9 until softened.\n2. Add bell pepper, carrots, and celery; cook for about 5 minutes.\n3. Stir in beans, corn, diced tomatoes, and vegetable broth.\n4. Add chili powder, cumin, salt, and pepper. Bring to a boil, then reduce heat and simmer for 20-30 minutes.\n5. Serve with optional toppings.\n\n2. **Vegetable Stir-Fry**\nIngredients:\n- 2 tablespoons sesame oil\n- 1 block firm tofu, cubed\n- 2 cups broccoli florets\n- 1 bell pepper, sliced\n- 1 cup snap peas\n- 2 carrots, sliced\n- 2 cloves garlic, minced\n- 1 tablespoon ginger, grated\n- 1/4 cup soy sauce\n- 2 tablespoons hoisin sauce\n- 1 tablespoon rice vinegar\n- 2 tablespoons water\n- Cooked rice or noodles, for serving\n- Sesame seeds and green onions, for garnish\n\nDirections:\n1. Heat sesame oil in a large pan or wok over medium-high heat. Add tofu and cook until golden on all sides. Remove and set aside.\n2. In the same pan, add broccoli, bell pepper, snap peas, and carrots. Cook until tender-crisp.\n3. Add garlic and ginger; cook for another minute.\n4. Stir in soy sauce, hoisin sauce, rice vinegar, and water. Cook for a few more minutes until the sauce thickens.\n5. Add the cooked tofu back to the pan and toss to coat.\n6. Serve over rice or noodles, garnished with sesame seeds and green onions.\n\n3. **Caprese Stuffed Portobello Mushrooms**\nIngredients:\n- 4 large portobello mushrooms, stems removed\n- 1 tablespoon olive oil\n- Salt and pepper to taste\n- 1 cup cherry tomatoes, halved\n- 1 cup fresh mozzarella, diced\n- 1/2 cup basil leaves, chopped\n- 2 tablespoons balsamic glaze\n\nDirections:\n1. Preheat the oven to 375\u00b0F (190\u00b0C).\n2. Brush the portobello mushrooms with olive oil and season with salt and pepper.\n3. Arrange mushrooms on a baking sheet and fill with cherry tomatoes, fresh mozzarella, and basil.\n4. Bake for 15-20 minutes, until mushrooms are tender and cheese is melted.\n5. Drizzle with balsamic glaze before serving.\n\n4. **Spinach and Ricotta Stuffed Shells**\nIngredients:\n- 20 jumbo pasta shells\n- 2 cups ricotta cheese\n- 1 cup grated mozzarella cheese, divided\n- 1/2 cup grated Parmesan cheese\n- 2 cups fresh spinach, chopped\n- 1 egg, beaten\n- 2 cups marinara sauce\n- 2 cloves garlic, minced\n- Salt and pepper to taste\n\nDirections:\n1. Preheat the oven to 375\u00b0F (190\u00b0C).\n2. Cook pasta shells according to package directions until al dente. Drain and let cool.\n3. In a bowl, mix ricotta, 1/2 cup mozzarella, Parmesan, spinach, egg, garlic, salt, and pepper.\n4. Spread 1 cup marinara sauce on the bottom of a baking dish.\n5. Stuff each shell with the ricotta mixture and place in the baking dish.\n6. Pour the remaining marinara sauce over the stuffed shells and sprinkle with remaining mozzarella.\n7. Cover with foil and bake for 25 minutes. Then remove foil and bake for an additional 10 minutes until bubbly and golden.\n\nThese recipes are flavorful and sure to please whether you're a vegetarian or simply looking for delicious meat-free meals!",
